      {
        "id": "CjZjjncXh0_CjvqD",
        "title": "Using EMG data to controlthe gripper",
        "content": {
          "type": "Question",
          "version": 1,
          "locked": false,
          "questionId": "6Kf1HW",
          "tiles": [
            {
              "title": "Question Prompt",
              "fixedPosition": true,
              "content": {
                "type": "Text",
                "format": "html",
                "text": [
                  "<p>Instead of using generated data, we want to use the EMG sensor data to make the gripper open and close.</p><p>If we just connect it to the gripper instead of the generator it won’t work. (You can try it out yourself if you want!)</p><p>Can you figure out why not?</p>"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "title": "Text 4",
              "content": {
                "type": "Text",
                "format": "html",
                "text": [
                  "<p>If you connect the EMG sensor directly to the gripper, the gripper will _________________________________________ because _________________________________________.</p>"
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "_zyD3CKk7jfXwhop",
        "title": "Text 6",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<h2>Planning a Solution</h2><p>How could you <strong>use</strong> or <strong>change</strong> the EMG sensor data to make the gripper understand it?</p><p>You can start by writing out what you want to do, even if you don’t know what blocks you would use yet.</p><p>You can use this sketch function. Drag the one below or open a new one by clicking the grey icon with the pencil.</p>"
          ]
        }
